title: Replies to initial written questions raised by Finance Committee Members in examining the Estimates of Expenditure 2007-08
question_text: The provision of $218 million in the Revised Estimate for 2006-07 was lower than that of the Original Estimate and close to the Actual Expenditure in 2005-06. Yet, the provision in the Draft Estimate for 2007-08 is still set at $228 million, which is comparable to that of last year’s Original Estimate. Please explain.
reply_text: The increase in the Draft Estimate for Programme (1) for 2007-08 over the Revised Estimate for 2006-07 is mainly due to the following reasons: (a) There is a saving of around $2 million in employment of temporary staff in 2006-07 due to a higher-than-expected turnover rate and recruitment difficulty during the year. It is expected that the relevant temporary staff will be recruited in 2007-08. Besides, the department will need to complete the assessment of unassessed lots in the New Territories as quickly as possible by engaging temporary staff and outsourcing part of the assessment work. It is envisaged that a total sum of about $5 million will be incurred in 2007-08 in engaging about 15 temporary staff and outsourcing; (b) Salary expenses in 2006-07 are some $1 million lower than estimated due to natural staff wastage. The vacancies will be filled in 2007-08; (c) There is an unspent provision of $0.8 million in 2006-07 due to difficulty in finding a suitable service provider for outsourcing of rural properties valuation work. The department is planning to award the contract soon, and $0.8 million is included in the Draft Estimate for 2007-08 for the purpose; and (d) There will be salary increments of $1 million for existing staff in 2007-08. Signature Name in block letters LO HING CHUNG Post Title Commissioner of Rating and Valuation Date 14.3.2007
